{"name": "wry-bokeh-helper", "metadata": {"name": "wry-bokeh-helper", "version": "0.4.0", "classifiers": ["Programming Language :: Python :: Implementation :: CPython", "Programming Language :: Python :: Implementation :: PyPy", "Programming Language :: Rust"], "home_page": null, "license": null, "documentation_url": null, "dependencies": ["pillow"], "summary": null, "upload_time": 1733110151}, "documentation": ["# wry-bokeh-helper\n\nBokeh is a great library for creating interactive plots in Python. However, it can be a bit verbose to use, especially when you want to export a plot to a standalone image file (which is fairly common in scientific publications). This library provides a simple wrapper around Bokeh that makes it easier to export them to image files.\n\n## Installation\n\n```bash\npip install wry-bokeh-helper\n```\n\n## Usage\n\n```python\nfrom bokeh.plotting import figure, show\nfrom wry_bokeh_helper import bokeh_to_image\n\n# prepare some data\nx = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]\ny = [6, 7, 2, 4, 5]\n\n# create a new plot with a title and axis labels\np = figure(title=\"Simple line example\", x_axis_label=\"x\", y_axis_label=\"y\")\n\n# add a line renderer with legend and line thickness\np.line(x, y, legend_label=\"Temp.\", line_width=2)\n\n\n# Export the plot to an image file\nimg = bokeh_to_image(plot, dpi=600)\nimg.show()\n\nbokeh_to_image(plot, dpi=300, filename=\"plot.png\")\n```\n\n"], "modules": [{"name": "wry_bokeh_helper", "documentation": [], "functions": [], "variables": [], "classes": [], "exports": [{"name": "wry_bokeh_helper.bokeh_to_image", "xref": {"fqname": "wry_bokeh_helper.bokeh_io.bokeh_to_image", "project": null}}]}, {"name": "wry_bokeh_helper._wry_bokeh_helper", "documentation": [], "functions": [], "variables": [], "classes": [], "exports": []}, {"name": "example.simple", "documentation": [], "functions": [], "variables": [{"name": "example.simple.p", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "example.simple.x", "type": null, "documentation"